Package edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic

Class Disjunction<E extends Expression>

java.lang.Object
edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic.Disjunction<E>
Type Parameters:
E - the type of the disjunction's arguments
All Implemented Interfaces:
Expression, Logical, Proposition, Simplifiable, Typed, Countable, Serializable, Comparable<Logical>, Iterable<E>
Direct Known Subclasses:
False, True
public class Disjunction<E extends Expression> extends Object implements Iterable<E>, Countable, Proposition
A disjunction is a proposition made up of zero to many arguments (or disjuncts) which are expressions of type boolean such that at least one of them must evaluate to true for the disjunction to be true.
Author:
Stephen G. Ware

    • simplify

      public Expression simplify()
      If any argument to this disjunction can be simplified to true, this method returns true. If any argument to this disjunction can be simplified to false it is removed. If there are no arguments, or if all arguments can be removed, this method returns false. If exactly one argument remains after simplification, it is returned instead of a disjunction. If two or more arguments remain, they will be put into their natural order.
      Specified by:
      simplify in interface Expression
      Specified by:
      simplify in interface Simplifiable
      Returns:
      a simplified expression, or this expression if nothing could be simplified

      public Value evaluate(State state)
      Returns true if and only if at least one disjunct of this disjunction evaluates to true. This method is short-circuiting, which means as soon as it encounters a true disjunct, it stops evaluating its arguments and returns true.

    • toEffect

      public Clause<Effect> toEffect()
      Description copied from interface: Expression
      Converts an expression whose type is boolean to disjunctive normal form (DNF) suitable to appear in the deterministic effect of an event. Because effects must be deterministic, this process must result in a disjunction of no more than one conjunctive clause whose atoms are effects. Because there will only be at most one clause, that clause is returned instead of a disjunction. If no clauses would be returned (in other words, if false would be returned), the null clause is returned.
      Specified by:
      toEffect in interface Expression
      Returns:
      a conjunctive clause whose atoms are effects
